description.value:
Length of medium - fine linen mummy-wrapping sewn together in modern times; edges are torn, ends are ragged; two lines of Hieroglyphic text including name of Horemakhbit and chapters from the Book of the Dead (ch. 1-3,15,17,18,19,24,25,28,29).
The weave is plain [warp-faced simple tabby] and the threads are S-spun; the stitch gauge is warp c.31-41 ends per 10mm and weft c.12-15 picks per 10mm. Many of the strips were sewn together via a patch of white modern linen, sewn with white S-plied cotton thread.

Belongs with: BM35245 - BM35260 + BM 35262 -BM 35265

description.value: Large fragment, one side of a cloth, possibly a long tunic in warp-faced plain weave. The wear is worst at the half-way point of the extant object, presumably reused as a mummy wrapping. The fine quality, undyed linen now greyish beige. Very worn with repairs/darning in two places; traces of resin. One plain selvedge with original horizontal edges lost. Warp is s-spin, s-spiced with c. 52 ends per cm; weft is s-spin, s-spiced, c. 22 picks per cm. The darning thread is s-spin, s-spliced, at mid-point, a later layer of darning over the earlier one hitches in both directions. At the second spot, a tear closed with oversewing with a hitched thread crossing.

Two textile fragments of undyed, medium-fine quality linen cloth. A is the main cloth; B is a small piece from another textile wrapped within A.

B) small, irregular fragment of fine linen, found wrapped within BM 6561a. Open weave; edged torn or ragged. description.value:
Two small textile fragments of fine, undyed linen cloth (mummy-wrapping?).
a) has part of a selvedge fringe, identified as Deir el-Bahri type 1(De Jonghe Fig.3) with discontinuous weft; other edges are torn and ragged. The weave is plain [warp-faced simple tabby] and the threads are S-spun and S-spliced; the stitch gauge is warp c.36 ends per 10mm and weft 15 picks per 10mm.

b) small fragment of linen cloth; medium-fine quality, without feature except for a black mark - possibly modern ink. Undyed, now dark cream. Worn. The weave is plain [warp-faced simple tabby] and the threads are S-spun and S-spliced; the stitch gauge is warp c.26 ends per 10mm and weft 16 picks per 10mm.

description.value:
Textile corner-fragment; undyed linen cloth, medium quality; plain selvedge; remains of hitched warp fringe; triple self-band; vertical edges torn, horizontal edges cut. Brown and blueish stains, the latter possibly modern and the former causing holes - iron mould? The weave is plain [warp-faced simple tabby] and the threads are S-spun; the stitch gauge is warp c.22 ends per 10mm and weft 10 picks per 10mm. The thread used for hitching the fringe is Z-plied, one row of knots worked from one side of the cloth, the other from the other side.
Presumably from a mummy.

description.value: Textile fragment; lower half of one side of undyed linen tunic; vertical side-seam joining two selvedges; twisted warp fringe preceded by triple self-band; stained with resin or bitumen from re-use on mummy. The weave is plain [warp-faced simple tabby] and the threads are S-spun and S-spliced; the stitch gauge is warp c.29 ends per 10mm and weft 10 picks per 10mm. The two plain selvedges are probably the same one folded back on itself - i.e. the two fringes are two ends of the same cloth. They include warp fringes without knots, each two threads Z-plied then S-twisted with neighbouring pair. The seam is oversewn/top sewn with S-spun, z-plied linen thread; darning thread ditto - all the darning lines of hitches are parallel to the warp holding and grouping the weft.
